# Code Style and Structure Rules

## Class Responsibility

Each class should map to one of the architecture's named responsibilities (see `architecture.mdc` and `ARCHITECTURE_Detailed.md`). Do not let a class accumulate responsibilities outside its stated role — e.g. `BuffSystem` owns Apply decisions and Tick lifecycle, not damage calculation or input handling. If a method you're adding doesn't fit the class's responsibility, it belongs somewhere else.

`AbilityBase` is the only abstract base class in this project. Do not introduce new abstract base classes — if behavior needs sharing, use an interface plus a private helper method.

## Naming Conventions

| Category | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Interfaces | `I` prefix, PascalCase | `IEvent`, `IAbility`, `IBuffEffect`, `IBuffApplier`, `IDamageModifier`, `IRandomProvider`, `IAbilityTargetProvider`, `ICooldownQuery`, `IEventBus` |
| Abstract classes | `Base` suffix | `AbilityBase` |
| ScriptableObject configs | `Config` suffix | `AbilityConfig`, `BuffConfig`, `PlayerConfig`, `EnemyConfig` |
| MonoBehaviour adapters | No suffix | `Player`, `Enemy`, `GameManager` |
| Event structs | `Event` suffix | `DamageEvent`, `BuffAppliedEvent`, `EntityDiedEvent` |
| Context types | `Context` suffix, both `readonly struct` (see `type-design.mdc`) | `DamageContext`, `AbilityContext` |
| Dependency bundles | `Deps` suffix, `readonly struct` | `AbilityTargetDeps` |
| Slot types | `Slot` suffix | `AbilitySlot` |
| Enums | PascalCase, no suffix | `StatType`, `DamageType`, `ModifierType`, `AbilityExecuteResult`, `TryExecuteResult` |
| Private fields | `_camelCase` with underscore prefix | `_currentHP`, `_handlers` |
| Public properties | PascalCase | `CurrentHP`, `MaxHP` |

## Formatting and C# Style

Follow the conventions in `Core/Events/IEvent.cs`, `IEventBus.cs`, and `EventBus.cs`.

**Braces and control flow**
- Allman style: opening `{` on its own line.
- Always use braces for `if` / `else`, even for single-line bodies.
- Prefer early return for guard clauses and no-op paths instead of deep nesting.

**File layout**
- `using` directives at the top, blank line, then block-scoped `namespace` matching the layer folder (e.g. `Core.Events`).
- One blank line between logical sections inside a type or method.
- End each file with a single trailing newline.

**Locals and initialization**
- Use `var` when the type is obvious from the right-hand side.
- Prefer target-typed `new()` for field/collection initialization (e.g. `new Dictionary<Type, Delegate>()`).

**Null checks and exceptions**
- Required arguments: `if (arg == null) { throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(arg)); }`
- Use `nameof(...)` in exception constructors.
- Use pattern matching where it clarifies intent (e.g. `if (del is not Action<T> action)`).
- Multi-line `throw` is allowed when the message is long; use `$"..."` interpolation for dynamic values, not `+` concatenation.

**Documentation** (see also `documentation.mdc`)
- Core public contracts (`IEvent`, `IEventBus`): XML docs on the interface.
- Implementations mirroring an interface: `/// <inheritdoc/>` on public members.
- Inline comments: only where a reader might assume a mistake; do not restate obvious code.

**Types**
- Concrete implementations not meant for extension: `public sealed class`.
- Private fields: `_camelCase`; use `readonly` when the reference does not change after construction.

## Folder Structure

```
Assets/
├── Scripts/
│   ├── Core/                ← IRandomProvider, StateMachine, IState
│   │   └── Events/          ← IEvent, IEventBus, EventBus, HealEvent, HpChangedEvent, CooldownStartedEvent, CooldownEndedEvent
│   ├── Character/           ← CharacterStats, Damageable, ICombatEntity
│   ├── Combat/
│   │   └── Events/          ← DamageEvent, EntityDiedEvent (Victim field)
│   ├── Ability/             ← AbilitySystem, AbilityTargetDeps, AbilitySlot, ICooldownQuery, IAbilityTargetProvider, DamageAbility, HealAbility, CooldownManager
│   ├── Buff/                ← IBuffApplier, BuffSystem, IBuffEffect, BuffConfig
│   │   └── Events/          ← BuffAppliedEvent, BuffRemovedEvent
│   └── Demo/                ← DashAbility, UnityRandomProvider, Player, Enemy, GameManager, PlayerInputHandler, EnemyAI, PlayerConfig, EnemyConfig, states, HUD
├── Tests/
├── Materials/
└── Scenes/
    └── Demo.unity
```

Do not place types in the wrong layer folder (e.g. a Combat type under Core/). Do not create speculative empty subfolders.

**Config ScriptableObject placement:** `AbilityConfig` and `BuffConfig` live in Ability/ and Buff/ respectively. `PlayerConfig` and `EnemyConfig` live in **Demo/** — they hold **`StatBaseEntry[]`** (for `CharacterStats` bases) + **`List<AbilitySlot>`** and may serialize Demo-layer `[SerializeReference] IAbility` implementations (e.g. `DashAbility`).

## Assembly Definitions

Each folder under `Scripts/` has its own `.asmdef` file. Names follow the pattern `Game.<LayerName>`:

| Folder | Assembly name | References |
|---|---|---|
| Core/ | `Game.Core` | (none) |
| Character/ | `Game.Character` | Core |
| Combat/ | `Game.Combat` | Core, Character |
| Ability/ | `Game.Ability` | Core, Combat, Character, Buff |
| Buff/ | `Game.Buff` | Core, Character |
| Demo/ | `Game.Demo` | all layers |
| Tests/ | `Game.Tests` | all gameplay layers (not Demo) |

Do not place code from one assembly into another assembly's folder. Do not create new `.asmdef` files without a concrete dependency-isolation reason (a future `Game.Editor` for editor-only tooling would qualify). Update this table if you do.
